- $p(n - 3) = (n - 3) \sum_{i} \text{dist}(P_i, P_{i+1})$
- $2d = \sum_{i} \sum_{j \in \text{univ} \setminus \{i-1, i, i+1\}} \text{dist}(P_i, P_j)$

For the second inequality $\frac{2d}{p} < \lfloor \frac{n}{2} \rfloor \lfloor \frac{n+1}{2} \rfloor - 2$:
- We need to bound $\frac{2d}{p}$ from above by a quadratic function of $n$

To prove these inequalities, we need to analyze the structure of the polygon and the relationships between the perimeter and the sum of diagonals.

