This is equivalent to $2d > p(n - 3)$.

Similarly, the upper bound: $\frac{2d}{p} < \left\lfloor \frac{n}{2} \right\rfloor \left\lfloor \frac{n+1}{2} \right\rfloor - 2$ is equivalent to $2d < p(\left\lfloor \frac{n}{2} \right\rfloor \left\lfloor \frac{n+1}{2} \right\rfloor - 2)$.

To prove these, we need relationships between $d$ and $p$.

